e who knew him. Through sharp and unremittingly ironic observations, Sytin describes with insight and amusement or dismay Tsarist Russia's bureaucracy, the Orthodox Church, the Imperial court, and a number of the country's most renowned writers, including Anton Chekhov, Leo Tolstoy, Maxim Gorky, and journalist Vlas Doroshevich. Sytin's memoir, a tale of Great Russian society voiced by a parvenu, depicts a pre-Revolutionary Russia of small shops, churches, convents, deep religious faith, and flawed rulers. While the Revolution eventually deprived Sytin of all means to continuing publishing, his resilience and enterprise remain a lasting legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aRuud, Charles A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSokolov, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoroka, Marina E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358753340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587533/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles